{"id":157,"date":"2021-01-11T13:33:49","date_gmt":"2021-01-11T13:33:49","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/?p=157"},"modified":"2021-02-14T10:08:10","modified_gmt":"2021-02-14T10:08:10","slug":"laser-delay-system-for-the-scanning-tct","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/laser-delay-system-for-the-scanning-tct\/","title":{"rendered":"Laser delay system for the scanning TCT"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>We have in our lab a <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http:\/\/particulars.si\/products.php?prod=LargeScanTCT.html\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"http:\/\/particulars.si\/products.php?prod=LargeScanTCT.html\" target=\"_blank\">scanning TCT by Particulars<\/a> which produces laser pulses. We want to do timing measurements with this so we need a time reference and a pulse. The best condition for this would be to have two separate laser pulses shifted in time by a fixed delay. One way to ensure that this delay is always the same for all of the pulses is to split the original pulse in two and then produce the delay by making one of the pulses to travel a longer distance. So today I assembled in the lab a system that implements such a delay method.<\/p>\n\n\n<style>.kb-table-of-content-nav.kb-table-of-content-id_192ec9-b1 .kb-table-of-content-wrap{padding-top:var(--global-kb-spacing-sm, 1.5rem);padding-right:var(--global-kb-spacing-sm, 1.5rem);padding-bottom:var(--global-kb-spacing-sm, 1.5rem);padding-left:var(--global-kb-spacing-sm, 1.5rem);}.kb-table-of-content-nav.kb-table-of-content-id_192ec9-b1 .kb-table-of-contents-title-wrap{padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;}.kb-table-of-content-nav.kb-table-of-content-id_192ec9-b1 .kb-table-of-contents-title{font-weight:regular;font-style:normal;}.kb-table-of-content-nav.kb-table-of-content-id_192ec9-b1 .kb-table-of-content-wrap .kb-table-of-content-list{font-weight:regular;font-style:normal;margin-top:var(--global-kb-spacing-sm, 1.5rem);margin-right:0px;margin-bottom:0px;margin-left:0px;}<\/style>\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Schematic<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>This is a scheme of the system that I assembled:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/laser-splitter-tct-schematic.svg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-158\" width=\"923\" height=\"257\"\/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>From left to right: the laser comes out from the TCT, it enters into a laser splitter which produces two identical pulses with 50 % of the energy each, then one of the pulses travels to a mixer and the other pulse travels through a &#8220;long&#8221; delay line before it reaches the mixer. Finally the two pulses are mixed back together into the same fiber and sent to the TCT again.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Components<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The components we bought all to Thorlabs and can be found below:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table is-style-regular\"><table><thead><tr><th>Element<\/th><th>Code<\/th><th>Quantity<\/th><\/tr><\/thead><tbody><tr><td>Laser splitter\/mixer<\/td><td><a href=\"https:\/\/www.thorlabs.com\/thorproduct.cfm?partnumber=TN1064R5F2A\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https:\/\/www.thorlabs.com\/thorproduct.cfm?partnumber=TN1064R5F2A\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">TN1064R5F2A<\/a><\/td><td>2 units<\/td><\/tr><tr><td>Delay optic fiber<\/td><td>NaN (see below)<\/td><td>20 meters<\/td><\/tr><tr><td>Connector<\/td><td><a href=\"https:\/\/www.thorlabs.com\/thorproduct.cfm?partnumber=ADAFC1\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https:\/\/www.thorlabs.com\/thorproduct.cfm?partnumber=ADAFC1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">ADAFC1<\/a><\/td><td>4 units<\/td><\/tr><\/tbody><\/table><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Optic fiber delay line<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>For the optic fiber delay line I used the <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https:\/\/www.thorlabs.com\/newgrouppage9.cfm?objectgroup_id=2410\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https:\/\/www.thorlabs.com\/newgrouppage9.cfm?objectgroup_id=2410\" target=\"_blank\">Custom Cable Configurator<\/a> with the following input:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/delay-optic-fiber-details.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-161\" width=\"717\" height=\"642\" srcset=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/delay-optic-fiber-details.png 921w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/delay-optic-fiber-details-300x269.png 300w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/delay-optic-fiber-details-768x689.png 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 717px) 100vw, 717px\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>When it arrived, the optic fiber had the following label:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-29-47-1024x710.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-173\" width=\"257\" height=\"178\" srcset=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-29-47-1024x710.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-29-47-300x208.jpg 300w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-29-47-768x533.jpg 768w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-29-47.jpg 1280w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 257px) 100vw, 257px\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Length of the delay line optic fiber<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<p>To calculate the length of the optic fiber I used the approximation that the speed of light inside the fiber is approximately two thirds that of vacuum. Thus <\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-mathml-mathmlblock\">\\[ \\text{Delay optic fiber length} = \\frac{2 c}{3}  \\Delta t \\]<script src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-includes\/js\/dist\/vendor\/wp-polyfill-inert.min.js?ver=3.1.2\" id=\"wp-polyfill-inert-js\"><\/script>\n<script src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-includes\/js\/dist\/vendor\/regenerator-runtime.min.js?ver=0.14.0\" id=\"regenerator-runtime-js\"><\/script>\n<script src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-includes\/js\/dist\/vendor\/wp-polyfill.min.js?ver=3.15.0\" id=\"wp-polyfill-js\"><\/script>\n<script src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-includes\/js\/dist\/hooks.min.js?ver=c6aec9a8d4e5a5d543a1\" id=\"wp-hooks-js\"><\/script>\n<script src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-includes\/js\/dist\/i18n.min.js?ver=7701b0c3857f914212ef\" id=\"wp-i18n-js\"><\/script>\n<script id=\"wp-i18n-js-after\">\nwp.i18n.setLocaleData( { 'text direction\\u0004ltr': [ 'ltr' ] } );\n<\/script>\n<script  async src=\"https:\/\/cdnjs.cloudflare.com\/ajax\/libs\/mathjax\/2.7.7\/MathJax.js?config=TeX-MML-AM_CHTML\" id=\"mathjax-js\"><\/script>\n<\/div>\n\n\n\n<p> where \\( c  \\approx 3 \\times 10 ^8 \\text{ m} \\text{ s}^{-1} \\)  and \\( \\Delta t \\) is the desired delay time. In my case \\( \\Delta t = 100 \\text{ ns} \\) so \\( \\text{Delay optic fiber length} \\approx 20 \\text{ m} \\). <\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The system assembly<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The assembly of the system is almost trivial. The only precaution to have is to be very careful when handling the fibers because they are too thin. Below there are two pictures of the system assembled outside the TCT and finally installed inside the TCT with all the connections made:<\/p>\n\n\n<style>.wp-block-kadence-advancedgallery .kb-gallery-type-grid.kb-gallery-id-_ba9f28-f7{margin:-5px;}.kb-gallery-type-grid.kb-gallery-id-_ba9f28-f7 .kadence-blocks-gallery-item{padding:5px;}.kb-gallery-id-_ba9f28-f7 .kadence-blocks-gallery-item .kb-gal-image-radius{border-radius:0px 0px 0px 0px;}<\/style>\n<div class=\"wp-block-kadence-advancedgallery kb-gallery-wrap-id-_ba9f28-f7\"><ul class=\"kb-gallery-ul kb-gallery-type-grid kb-gallery-id-_ba9f28-f7 kb-gallery-caption-style-bottom-hover kb-gallery-filter-none kb-gallery-magnific-init\" data-item-selector=\".kadence-blocks-gallery-item\" data-image-filter=\"none\" data-lightbox-caption=\"false\" data-columns-xxl=\"2\" data-columns-xl=\"2\" data-columns-lg=\"2\" data-columns-md=\"2\" data-columns-sm=\"1\" data-columns-xs=\"1\"><li class=\"kadence-blocks-gallery-item\"><div class=\"kadence-blocks-gallery-item-inner\"><figure class=\"kb-gallery-figure kb-gallery-item-has-link kadence-blocks-gallery-item-hide-caption kb-has-image-ratio-inherit\"><a href=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-57.jpg\" class=\"kb-gallery-item-link\"><div class=\"kb-gal-image-radius\" style=\"max-width:1024px\"><div class=\"kb-gallery-image-contain kadence-blocks-gallery-intrinsic kb-gallery-image-ratio-inherit\" style=\"padding-bottom:97.0703125%\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-57-1024x994.jpg\" width=\"1024\" height=\"994\" alt=\"\" data-full-image=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-57.jpg\" data-light-image=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-57.jpg\" data-id=\"169\" data-link=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/?attachment_id=169\" class=\"wp-image-169undefined\" srcset=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-57-1024x994.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-57-300x291.jpg 300w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-57-768x746.jpg 768w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-57.jpg 1280w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/div><\/div><\/a><\/figure><\/div><\/li><li class=\"kadence-blocks-gallery-item\"><div class=\"kadence-blocks-gallery-item-inner\"><figure class=\"kb-gallery-figure kb-gallery-item-has-link kadence-blocks-gallery-item-hide-caption kb-has-image-ratio-inherit\"><a href=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-58.jpg\" class=\"kb-gallery-item-link\"><div class=\"kb-gal-image-radius\" style=\"max-width:1024px\"><div class=\"kb-gallery-image-contain kadence-blocks-gallery-intrinsic kb-gallery-image-ratio-inherit\" style=\"padding-bottom:61.1328125%\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-58-1024x626.jpg\" width=\"1024\" height=\"626\" alt=\"\" data-full-image=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-58.jpg\" data-light-image=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-58.jpg\" data-id=\"170\" data-link=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/?attachment_id=170\" class=\"wp-image-170undefined\" srcset=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-58-1024x626.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-58-300x183.jpg 300w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-58-768x469.jpg 768w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-17-58.jpg 1280w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/div><\/div><\/a><\/figure><\/div><\/li><\/ul><\/div>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Results<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>At a first glance, the system is behaving as expected. In the image below we see two pulses coming out from an AC-LGAD detector each corresponding to each of the two laser pulses. The delay time between the two pulses is \\( \\Delta t \\approx 98.7 \\text{ ns} \\) as designed. The system was no further characterized yet.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"663\" src=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-21-07-1024x663.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-171\" srcset=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-21-07-1024x663.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-21-07-300x194.jpg 300w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-21-07-768x497.jpg 768w, https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-content\/uploads\/2021\/01\/photo_2021-01-11_14-21-07.jpg 1280w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>We have in our lab a scanning TCT by Particulars which produces laser pulses. We want to do timing measurements with this so we need a time reference and a pulse. The best condition for this would be to have two separate laser pulses shifted in time by a fixed delay. One way to ensure &hellip;<\/p>\n<p class=\"read-more\"> <a class=\"\" href=\"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/laser-delay-system-for-the-scanning-tct\/\"> <span class=\"screen-reader-text\">Laser delay system for the scanning TCT<\/span> Read More &raquo;<\/a><\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":171,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"inline_featured_image":false,"footnotes":""},"categories":[1],"tags":[4,6],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/157"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/msenger.web.cern.ch\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"ht